d Kingdom":"Armley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ingleby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Ingleby (in Lincolnshire, Yorkshire, and Derbyshire). The placenames mean ‘farmstead of the English’, from Old English <i>Engle</i> ‘English’ (genitive plural <i>Engla</i>) + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Thomas Ingleby was born about 1305, in Armley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Thomas Ingleby and Edeline Ingleby. He had at least 1 son with Katherine MAULEVERER. His occupation is listed as judge of the king's bench ( 30 sept 1361), m.p for yorkshire ( 1348), lord of the manor of ripley in Ripley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He died about 1369, at the age of 66."},"et":{"Abt 1305–About 1369":"umbes 1305–umbes 1369","1305–1369":"1305–1369","–1375":"–1375","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1293–Female":"1293–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1318–Male":"1318–Surnud","1290–1375":"1290–1375","1305":"1305","1369":"1369","about 1308":"umbes 1308","About 1369":"umbes 1369","1375":"1375","1330":"1330","1293":"1293","Abt 1318":"umbes 1318","1318":"1318","Abt 1305":"umbes 1305","1290":"1290","Ripley, Yorkshire, England":"Ripley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Armley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Armley, Yorksh